          "Cluster Description",
          "Implications",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Clustering",
          "Higher Education",
          "B-Learning",
          "92 undergraduate students to build SRL indicators\n\n38 students for “testing” purposes",
          "1 course in a Computer Science Program",
          "LMS logs, \nQuestionnaires",
          "Winne’s SRL Model",
          "[Self-Reported SRL Tags]",
          "Logs were categorized into different SRL constructs which the authors called Observed SRL Tags. \n\nMSLQ answers are clustered using Hierarchical Clustering.\n\nLMS logs were filtered in order to only account for the ones relating with the assignment and the logs were aggregated into sessions. \n\n\n\n",
          "Hierarchical Clustering",
          "{Weighted Cohen’s Kappa: 0.74 - Agreement between self-report and SRL tags}",
          "3",
          "Cluster 1: High SRL learners, \n\nCluster 2: Moderate SRL learners\n\nCluster 3: Low SRL learners",
          "Being able to observed students’ SRL behaviors in the context of an LMS could be pivotal towards developing better assignments and learning activity structures.\n\n",
          "Authors evaluate self-report measures and how they map with Log behavior in the context of one/more than one assignment.\n\nAfter tagging behavior to different SRL dimensions, the authors check the agreement between what was observed behavior AND Self-Reported Behavior.\n\nResults show that it is possible to achieve a level of partial agreement based on sequences.",
          "Self-selection bias-participantes were rewarded with participation.\n\nLMS are a partial and incomplete picture of learner behavior."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
